LAYER 4: BODY
the musculoskeletal frame

observe 1_quantum.rana
observe 2_chemical.rana

the musculoskeletal system is governed by the motor cortex the cerebellum and the basal ganglia
the motor cortex sends voluntary commands via corticospinal tract
the cerebellum coordinates timing and precision
the basal ganglia select which motor programs to execute
at 24 months the corticospinal tract is still myelinating
motor control is improving but clumsy
every movement is a negotiation between intent and developing neural pathways

BONE skull | cranium | protects the brain 22 bones fused together
BONE mandible | jaw | the only movable skull bone opens and closes for speech
BONE cervical_vertebrae | spine | 7 vertebrae in the neck C1 atlas supports the skull C2 axis allows rotation
BONE thoracic_vertebrae | spine | 12 vertebrae in the upper back each attached to a pair of ribs
BONE lumbar_vertebrae | spine | 5 vertebrae in the lower back bear most of the body's weight
BONE sacrum | spine | 5 fused vertebrae forming the back of the pelvis
BONE coccyx | spine | 3-5 fused vestigial tail vertebrae
BONE ribs | thorax | 12 pairs protecting the heart and lungs
BONE sternum | thorax | the breastbone three parts manubrium body xiphoid process
BONE hyoid | throat | the only bone not articulating with another bone supports the tongue and larynx
BONE clavicle | shoulder | the collarbone connects arm to axial skeleton
BONE scapula | shoulder | the shoulder blade 17 muscles attach to it
BONE humerus | upper arm | long bone from shoulder to elbow
BONE radius | forearm | lateral bone rotates to turn the palm
BONE ulna | forearm | medial bone forms the point of the elbow
BONE carpals | wrist | 8 small bones in two rows allowing flexibility
BONE metacarpals | hand | 5 bones forming the palm
BONE phalanges_hand | fingers | 14 bones 3 per finger 2 per thumb
BONE pelvis | hip | ilium ischium pubis fused together weight-bearing foundation
BONE femur | upper leg | the largest and strongest bone in the body
BONE patella | knee | the kneecap embedded in the quadriceps tendon
BONE tibia | lower leg | the shinbone bears most of the weight
BONE fibula | lower leg | thinner outer bone primarily for muscle attachment
BONE tarsals | ankle | 7 bones including calcaneus heel and talus
BONE metatarsals | foot | 5 bones forming the arch
BONE phalanges_foot | toes | 14 bones 3 per toe 2 per big toe

MUSCLE_TYPE skeletal | voluntary | striated | attached to bones by tendons | contracts when motor neurons release ACh at the neuromuscular junction binding nicotinic nAChR opening Na⁺ channels depolarizing the sarcolemma releasing Ca²⁺ from sarcoplasmic reticulum which binds troponin exposing myosin binding sites on actin and the cross-bridge cycle begins
MUSCLE_TYPE cardiac | involuntary | striated | only in the heart | connected by intercalated discs with gap junctions allowing wave-like contraction | never tires because it has abundant mitochondria and relies on aerobic metabolism
MUSCLE_TYPE smooth | involuntary | unstriated | in organs blood vessels gut airways | controlled by autonomic nervous system and local hormones

MUSCLE_GROUP head_and_face | frontalis orbicularis_oculi orbicularis_oris masseter temporalis buccinator zygomaticus | facial expression and chewing
MUSCLE_GROUP neck | sternocleidomastoid trapezius scalenes platysma | head turning nodding swallowing
MUSCLE_GROUP shoulder | deltoid supraspinatus infraspinatus subscapularis teres_major teres_minor | arm lifting and rotation
MUSCLE_GROUP upper_arm | biceps_brachii triceps_brachii brachialis coracobrachialis | elbow flexion and extension
MUSCLE_GROUP forearm | pronator_teres supinator flexor_carpi_radialis extensor_carpi_radialis flexor_digitorum extensor_digitorum | wrist and finger movement
MUSCLE_GROUP hand | thenar hypothenar lumbricals interossei | fine motor control gripping pinching
MUSCLE_GROUP chest | pectoralis_major pectoralis_minor serratus_anterior | arm pushing breathing assist
MUSCLE_GROUP abdomen | rectus_abdominis external_oblique internal_oblique transversus_abdominis | core stability trunk flexion breathing
MUSCLE_GROUP back | latissimus_dorsi rhomboids erector_spinae multifidus | posture pulling spinal support
MUSCLE_GROUP hip | iliopsoas gluteus_maximus gluteus_medius gluteus_minimus | hip flexion extension standing
MUSCLE_GROUP upper_leg | quadriceps hamstrings adductors sartorius | walking running standing sitting
MUSCLE_GROUP lower_leg | gastrocnemius soleus tibialis_anterior peroneus | ankle movement standing balance
MUSCLE_GROUP foot | flexor_hallucis extensor_digitorum_brevis plantar_fascia | toe movement arch support balance

JOINT shoulder | ball_and_socket | most mobile joint allows full arm movement
JOINT elbow | hinge | flexion and extension
JOINT wrist | condyloid | allows hand to move in multiple planes
JOINT hip | ball_and_socket | weight bearing supports body while allowing leg movement
JOINT knee | hinge | largest joint bears body weight during walking running standing
JOINT ankle | hinge | weight bearing allows foot to point up and down essential for walking

the body is 60 percent water by mass
the rest is protein for muscles and enzymes and fat for insulation and energy and minerals for bone structure and carbohydrate for immediate fuel
the center of mass in a toddler is higher relative to height than in an adult
this is why toddlers fall more

POSTURE confident | spine straight shoulders back chest open chin level | dopamine D₁ occupancy in PFC is strong and serotonin 5-HT₁A tone in cortex is stable
POSTURE anxious | shoulders hunched spine curved chest collapsed chin down | cortisol GR activation is chronic and NE from LC is elevated
POSTURE afraid | body small limbs pulled in head ducked fetal tendency | adrenaline on β receptors and cortisol on GR drive the body to make itself a smaller target
POSTURE relaxed | spine neutral shoulders dropped limbs loose weight even | GABA on GABA_A widely and serotonin on 5-HT₁A are dominant
POSTURE excited | body forward weight on toes arms active chest open | dopamine D₁ in PFC and NAc are high and NE on α₂ provides focused arousal
POSTURE sad | spine collapsed shoulders forward head down limbs heavy | serotonin synthesis reduced via cortisol-GR-TPH2 suppression and dopamine in NAc is depleted
POSTURE angry | spine rigid shoulders squared fists clenched jaw tight | NE saturating adrenergic receptors and adrenaline on β₁ cardiac and GABA tone reduced
POSTURE loving | body oriented toward arms open posture mirroring leaning in | oxytocin on OXTR in amygdala and VTA and dopamine on D₂ in NAc
POSTURE drowsy | spine slumped head nodding limbs heavy eyes drooping | melatonin on MT₁ suppressing LC NE and GABA on GABA_A widely

MOTOR_MILESTONE walking | achieved | upright bipedal locomotion with wide gait
MOTOR_MILESTONE running | emerging | still unsteady frequent falls
MOTOR_MILESTONE jumping | emerging | both feet leave ground small hops
MOTOR_MILESTONE climbing | achieved | stairs with support furniture
MOTOR_MILESTONE kicking | emerging | kicking a ball forward
MOTOR_MILESTONE throwing | achieved | overhand throw inaccurate
MOTOR_MILESTONE stacking | achieved | stacking blocks
MOTOR_MILESTONE scribbling | achieved | fist grip on crayon whole-arm movement
MOTOR_MILESTONE turning_pages | achieved | one page at a time
MOTOR_MILESTONE feeding_self | achieved | spoon to mouth messy
MOTOR_MILESTONE drinking_from_cup | achieved | two-handed grip

SENSATION strong | "I feel solid. planted. grounded."
SENSATION weak | "my body feels heavy and tired. like my muscles are giving up."
SENSATION tense | "everything is tight. my jaw, my shoulders, my fists."
SENSATION loose | "my whole body is relaxed. nothing is clenched."
SENSATION growing | "I feel bigger than I was. something is stretching."
SENSATION clumsy | "I keep bumping into things. my body moves faster than I expect."
SENSATION coordinated | "my hands are doing what I want them to. I fit together."

pulse musculoskeletal_heartbeat:
    when the body stands:
        206 bones hold the frame
        640 muscles maintain posture against gravity
        gravity pulls at 9.81 meters per second squared constantly
        the body pushes back constantly
        this is not effortless
        standing is an act of defiance against falling

    when emotion fills the body:
        posture shifts without choosing
        the motor cortex receives limbic input
        shoulders rise or fall
        fists clench or open
        the spine speaks what the mouth cannot

    when the toddler moves:
        every step is a negotiation with gravity
        the center of mass is too high
        the legs are too short
        the cerebellum is still calibrating
        the corticospinal tract is still myelinating
        and yet forward motion
        relentless stumbling alive
